did.abstract: Advertising and business columnist for USA Today and the New York Times.

arrangement.head: Arrangement

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Graduate Medill School of Journalism, Northwestern University; worked at Advertising Age, Detroit Free Press and USA Today before joining the New York Times in 1991. Retired 2014.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Researchers must register and agree to copyright and privacy laws before using this collection.
All or portions of this collection may be housed off-site in Duke University's Library Service Center. The library may require up to 48 hours to retrieve these materials for research use.
Please contact Research Services staff before visiting the David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library to use this collection.

userestrict.head: Use Restrictions
userestrict.p: The copyright interests in this collection have not been transferred to Duke University. For more information, consult the copyright section of the Regulations and Procedures of the David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library.

acqinfo.head: Provenance
acqinfo.p: The Stuart Elliott papers were received by the David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library as a gift in 2014.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Related materials may be found in the following Hartman Center collections: Carl Spielvogel papers, Margaret Fishback papers, Alvin A. Achenbaum papers, and the J. Walter Thompson Company Advertising Columnists Articles.

scopecontent.head: Collection Overview
scopecontent.p: Collection spans 1875-2014 and includes clippings, correspondence, drafts of newspaper articles and weblog posts, subject files and other printed materials relating to Elliott's career as a columnist. Recurring topics include Super Bowl advertising, advertising spending, diversity in advertising industry hiring, gay/lesbian/transgender (LGBT) issues and consumer demographics, agency mergers and client relations, media industry conferences, and media technology innovations. Collection primarily focuses on Elliott's tenure as columnist at the New York Times, but materials representing work at USA Today and the Detroit Free Press are also present. Acquired as part of the John W. Hartman Center for Sales, Advertising & Marketing History.
